The important thing to understand about Bittensor is that it is not like hashrate mining. Once you have gotten the infrastructure software (Bittensor) installed, the miner or validator codebase is going to be different depending on which subnet(s) you are working in. There is a very general checklist for preparing to mine or validate here: https://docs.bittensor.com/subnets/checklist-for-validating-mining but it does not contain step-by-step instructions for any particular model or version of node software, which will be subnet-specific.

You can explore the different subnets through the channels -- check the pinned posts in the subnet's channel to find links to the subnet's code, any additional information such as tutorials or guides, etc. Other than the "subnets" pages on Taostats.io, which is a third-party product, there is no centrally-maintained guide to the subnets, as ownership of the subnets is subject to frequent changes.

Note that because the code is different in each subnet, and trying to accomplish something different, it means that there is not really going to be an easy way for us to recommend subnets for newcomers, or for specific computer specifications, etc. it will be up to you to figure out which one(s) best match your equipment, resources, and skill level, if you are interested in exploring further. 🙂

# How can I get started mining/validating?

The important thing to understand about Bittensor is that it's not like hashrate mining.  Once you have gotten the infrastructure software (Bittensor) installed, the miner or validator codebase is going to be different depending on which subnet(s) you're working in.  There is a very general checklist for preparing to mine or validate here: https://docs.bittensor.com/subnets/checklist-for-validating-mining but it does not contain step-by-step instructions for any particular model or version of node software, which will be subnet-specific.

You can explore the different subnets through the channels in the Subnet and Testnet categories of this Discord. If you have any questions about what equipment/resources/knowledge is required in a particular subnet, check the pinned posts in the subnet's channel.

Note that because the code is different in each subnet, and trying to accomplish something different, it means that there is not really going to be an easy way for us to recommend subnets for newcomers, or for specific computer specifications, etc.  It'll be up to you to figure out which one(s) best match your equipment, resources, and skill level, if you are interested in exploring further. : )

The important thing to understand about Bittensor is that it's not like hashrate mining.
